'''Social policies''' are devised to solve or prevent [[social problems]] and evils.

For example, under the purely [[free enterprise]] system or [[market economy]] those individuals who are unable to contribute to the [[production process]] like the [[unemployed]], old people and sick or disabled would not receive any [[income]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} Another example of problems that may arise under [[capitalism]] are [[unintended consequence|side effects]] of [[industrial production]] processes like [[noise]] and all kinds of [[pollution]]s.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} [[Governments]] of some countries feel obliged to make available to the [[general public|public]] certain amounts of basic [[good (economics)|goods]] and [[service (economics)|services]] called [[merit wants]] that contribute to the basic [[Quality of life|welfare]] of the [[society]] regardles of their income levels.<ref>''Modern Economics'', Mentor Books</ref>

